Author-Name: John R. Graham 
Author-Workplace-Name: Fuqua School of Business, Duke University 
Title: How Big Are the Tax Benefits of Debt? 
Abstract:
 I integrate under firm-specific benefit functions to estimate that the
 capitalized tax benefit of debt equals 9.7 percent of firm value (or as
 low as 4.3 percent, net of personal taxes). The typical firm could double
 tax benefits by issuing debt until the marginal tax benefit begins to
 decline. I infer how aggressively a firm uses debt by observing the shape
 of its tax benefit function. Paradoxically, large, liquid, profitable
 firms with low expected distress costs use debt conservatively. Product
 market factors, growth options, low asset collateral, and planning for
 future expenditures lead to conservative debt usage. Conservative debt
 policy is persistent. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
