Author-Name: Jennifer N. Carpenter 
Author-Workplace-Name: Department of Finance, Stern School of Business, New York University 
Title: Does Option Compensation Increase Managerial Risk Appetite? 
Abstract:
 This paper solves the dynamic investment problem of a risk averse manager
 compensated with a call option on the assets he controls. Under the
 manager's optimal policy, the option ends up either deep in or deep out of
 the money. As the asset value goes to zero, volatility goes to infinity.
 However, the option compensation does not strictly lead to greater risk
 seeking. Sometimes, the manager's optimal volatility is less with the
 option than it would be if he were trading his own account. Furthermore,
 giving the manager more options causes him to reduce volatility. Copyright The American Finance Association 2000. 
